{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "One such approximation is provided by RPA, where the interaction kernel in the Bethe-Salpeter equation is taken to be a combination of a particle-hole scattering event, and a particle-hole annihilation and creation event -both due to the densitydensity interaction.",
    "In the terminology of diagram-enthusiasts: the approximate Bethe-Salpeter equation is obtained by summing the geometric series generated by both bubble and ladder diagrams.",
    "Crucially, the RPA approximation is a conserving approximation in the sense of Kadanoff and Baym [226], meaning that it preserves all symmetries and hence respects the Ward identities.Poles in G 2 (ω) give access to the spectrum of particle-hole excitations.",
    "It turns out that the equation which determines the locations of the poles in the RPA approximation is exactly the same as the linearized TDHF equation [227].",
    "This equivalence between RPA and TDHF makes it clear that (1) RPA is indeed a conserving approximation, as the TDVP formalism explicitly preserves all symmetries, and (2) solutions to the linearized TDHF equation provide an approximation for the energies of particlehole excitations."
  ],
